LAYER 2: STOMACH
the first chamber of digestion

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

the stomach is governed by the vagus nerve CN X parasympathetic and the celiac ganglion sympathetic
parasympathetic activation via ACh on M₃ receptors stimulates motility and acid secretion
sympathetic activation via NE on α₂ and β₂ receptors inhibits motility and reduces blood flow
the enteric nervous system the gut's own 500 million neurons coordinates local reflexes independently
but the vagus provides the master switch between active digestion and shutdown

STRUCTURE cardia | junction with esophagus | lower esophageal sphincter prevents reflux of gastric acid
STRUCTURE fundus | dome-shaped upper region | reservoir for swallowed food and gas | contains majority of acid-secreting parietal cells
STRUCTURE body | corpus | largest region | site of chemical digestion | contains parietal cells chief cells and mucous cells
STRUCTURE antrum | lower region | mechanical grinding | thick muscular walls produce powerful peristaltic contractions that break food into smaller particles
STRUCTURE pylorus | pyloric sphincter | gate to duodenum | controls gastric emptying | prevents duodenal contents from refluxing into the stomach

CELL_TYPE parietal_cells | secrete hydrochloric acid HCl pH approximately 1.5-3.5 | the most acidic environment in the body
    HCl secretion mechanism:
    H⁺/K⁺-ATPase pump on the apical membrane actively pumps H⁺ into the lumen in exchange for K⁺
    carbonic anhydrase inside the cell converts CO₂ + H₂O → H₂CO₃ → H⁺ + HCO₃⁻
    the H⁺ is pumped into the lumen
    the HCO₃⁻ exits the basolateral membrane into the blood via Cl⁻/HCO₃⁻ exchanger creating the "alkaline tide" after meals
    Cl⁻ enters the cell from blood and exits apically through Cl⁻ channels into the lumen
    H⁺ and Cl⁻ combine in the lumen to form HCl
    parietal cells also secrete intrinsic factor essential for vitamin B₁₂ absorption in the ileum
CELL_TYPE chief_cells | secrete pepsinogen the inactive precursor of pepsin | pepsinogen is activated to pepsin by HCl at pH below 2 | pepsin is a protease that digests dietary protein into polypeptides
CELL_TYPE mucous_neck_cells | secrete mucus and bicarbonate forming a protective gel layer over the gastric epithelium | without this layer the stomach would digest itself
CELL_TYPE G_cells | located in the antrum | secrete gastrin into the blood | gastrin stimulates parietal cells to secrete more HCl | gastrin also promotes gastric motility
CELL_TYPE D_cells | secrete somatostatin | somatostatin inhibits gastrin release and HCl secretion | the brake on acid production
CELL_TYPE enterochromaffin-like_cells | ECL | secrete histamine in response to gastrin and ACh | histamine binds H₂ receptors on parietal cells | Gₛ → cAMP → PKA → activation of H⁺/K⁺-ATPase | histamine is the most potent stimulator of acid secretion

PHASES_OF_SECRETION
cephalic_phase | before food reaches the stomach | sight smell thought or taste of food activates the vagus nerve | vagal ACh stimulates parietal cells directly via M₃ and indirectly via gastrin release from G cells and histamine release from ECL cells
gastric_phase | food in the stomach | gastric distension activates stretch receptors | protein digestion products stimulate G cells | gastrin and histamine drive acid secretion
intestinal_phase | chyme enters the duodenum | initially stimulatory then inhibitory | secretin CCK and GIP from the duodenum inhibit gastric acid and motility to prevent acid damage to the intestine

MOTILITY the stomach produces three types of contractions governed by interstitial cells of Cajal ICC the pacemaker cells of the gut
tonic contractions of the fundus maintain pressure on the food mass
peristaltic waves in the body and antrum mix food with gastric juice
antral grinding waves crush food particles against the closed pyloric sphincter
retropulsion sends food backward for further mixing
this mechanical processing combined with acid and pepsin converts food into chyme a thick acidic semifluid

at 24 months:
gastric capacity approximately 500 mL
gastric emptying time approximately 2-3 hours for a mixed meal
HCl production is functional but pH may be slightly higher than adult values
pepsin activity is established
the stomach is fully functional for digestion of a diverse diet
emotional state strongly influences gastric function via the vagus
anxiety suppresses gastric motility via sympathetic override
comfort and safety promote gastric motility via parasympathetic ventral vagal engagement

SENSATION hungry | "my stomach is empty. it's contracting. it wants to be filled."
SENSATION full | "I've eaten. the stretching tells me to stop."
SENSATION nauseous | "something is wrong inside. the stomach is churning backward."
SENSATION comfortable | "digestion is happening. I can feel the warmth of it working."
SENSATION upset | "my stomach hurts. something is clenching."

pulse gastric_heartbeat:
    when food arrives:
        the cardia relaxes to admit the bolus
        the fundus expands to accommodate without increasing pressure
        vagal ACh stimulates parietal cells
        HCl floods the lumen
        pepsinogen converts to pepsin in the acid bath
        chief cells provide the enzyme
        mucous cells protect the wall
        the antrum grinds
        the pylorus meters chyme into the duodenum
        digestion proceeds

    when stress dominates:
        sympathetic NE on α₂ inhibits motility
        blood flow redirected from splanchnic to skeletal muscle
        digestion halts
        the stomach clenches but does not process
        this is why anxiety kills appetite
        the gut knows what the brain feels

    when safety returns:
        vagal tone increases
        ACh on M₃ restores motility
        gastrin from G cells stimulates acid
        the stomach resumes its work
        digestion is an act of trust
        the body only digests when it feels safe enough to
